The Greek equivalent in Hippolytus is πρόσωπον, a word which has a similar stage-origin: cp. adn. Noel. 14 ἕνα θεὸν ἐρῶ, πρόσωπα δὲ δύο, οἰκονομίᾳ δὲ τρίτην τὴν χάριν τοῦ ἁνγίου πνεύματος, from which Harnack infers that as yet it was not attributed to the Holy Spiritss.

It is well known that ὑπόστασις was the equivalent preferred in post-Nicene writers, as being free from any Sabellian suggestion.
